<h3><a href="#a-good-idea-with-bad-usage-devurandom-2014" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor" id="user-content-a-good-idea-with-bad-usage-devurandom-2014"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="octicon octicon-link" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><a href="http://insanecoding.blogspot.co.uk/2014/05/a-good-idea-with-bad-usage-devurandom.html" rel="nofollow">A good idea with bad usage: /dev/urandom</a> (2014)</h3>
<p><strong>Released</strong>: May 3, 2014</p>
<p>Mentions many ways to make <code>/dev/urandom</code> fail on Linux/BSD.</p>
<h3><a href="#why-invest-in-application-security-2015" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor" id="user-content-why-invest-in-application-security-2015"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="octicon octicon-link" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><a href="https://paragonie.com/white-paper/2015-why-invest-application-security" rel="nofollow">Why Invest in Application Security?</a> (2015)</h3>
<p><strong>Released</strong>: June 21, 2015</p>
<p>Running a business requires being cost-conscious and minimizing unnecessary spending. The benefits of ensuring in the security of your application are invisible to most companies, so often times they neglect to invest in secure software development as a cost-saving measure. What these companies don't realize is the potential cost (both financial and to brand reputation) a preventable data compromise can incur.</p>
<p><strong>The average data breach costs millions of dollars in damage.</strong></p>
<p>Investing more time and personnel to develop secure software is, for most companies, worth it to minimize this unnecessary risk to their bottom line.</p>
<h3><a href="#be-wary-of-one-time-pads-and-other-crypto-unicorns-2015" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor" id="user-content-be-wary-of-one-time-pads-and-other-crypto-unicorns-2015"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="octicon octicon-link" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a><a href="https://freedom-to-tinker.com/blog/jbonneau/be-wary-of-one-time-pads-and-other-crypto-unicorns/" rel="nofollow">Be wary of one-time pads and other crypto unicorns</a> (2015)</h3>
<p><strong>Released</strong>: March 25, 2015</p>
<p>A <strong>must-read</strong> for anyone looking to build their own cryptography features.</p>
